To implement a LIFO stack using two queues, we need to make sure that the front of the queue behaves like the top of the stack. Here is how we can do it:

1. We will maintain two queues, `q1` and `q2`.
2. Whenever we push an element, we will insert it into `q1`.
3. When we need to pop an element, we will move all the elements except the last one from `q1` to `q2`. The last element in `q1` will be the top element of the stack, which we will return after removing it from `q1`.
4. If we need to get the top element of the stack, we will move all the elements except the last one from `q1` to `q2`. The last element in `q1` will be the top element of the stack, which we will return. We will also move this element to `q2` so that `q1` remains empty while `q2` now contains all the elements except the top element.
5. To check if the stack is empty, we will check if both `q1` and `q2` are empty.

Here is the implementation of the MyStack class:

```
class MyStack {
    private Queue<Integer> q1 = new LinkedList<>();
    private Queue<Integer> q2 = new LinkedList<>();

    public void push(int x) {
        q1.add(x);
    }

    public int pop() {
        while (q1.size() > 1) {
            q2.add(q1.poll());
        }
        int top = q1.poll();
        Queue<Integer> temp = q1;
        q1 = q2;
        q2 = temp;
        return top;
    }

    public int top() {
        while (q1.size() > 1) {
            q2.add(q1.poll());
        }
        int top = q1.poll();
        q2.add(top);
        Queue<Integer> temp = q1;
        q1 = q2;
        q2 = temp;
        return top;
    }

    public boolean empty() {
        return q1.isEmpty() && q2.isEmpty();
    }
}
